Brick 3 of the self-hosting arc: an arithmetic-expression PARSER written in
Verbose, with operator precedence, consuming the brick-2 token stream.

1. Declare a concept group holding the token types from brick 2 (a classified
   Token and a cons-list TokenList), an arithmetic AST (a numeric leaf, a
   binary-operator node, and an error leaf), and a parse result that pairs an
   AST node with the token index where parsing of it ended.

2. A scanner state holds the source text and a byte position.

3. Skip spaces: advance the position past ASCII spaces.

4. Count the run of decimal digits starting at the position.

5. Compute ten to the power n for small n (digit-position weight).

6. Decode the decimal value of the digit run at the position.

7. Classify the operator or punctuation at the position (two-char operators
   before one-char ones).

8. The byte length of an operator (two for two-char operators, one otherwise).

9. Recognize the next core lexeme at the position: a number, an operator, or
   end of input.

10. The byte offset just past the next token.

11. Scan the whole source into a cons-list of tokens with a trailing end-of-input
    sentinel.

12. Drop the first n cons cells of a token list (a list plus an index).

13. Token accessors: the head token of a list, the kind code of a token, and the
    literal value carried by a number token.

14. Peek the kind code and the literal value of the token at a given index.

15. The parser carries the whole token list plus the current index. A fold state
    additionally carries the left-associative accumulator AST. Two accessors pull
    the node and the next-index out of a parse result. (Language note: a
    block-form match cannot currently be the right-hand side of a let binding —
    it is only legal in the final assignment position — so destructuring a parse
    result is factored into these two tiny rules.)

16. Parse a primary: a parenthesized expression, or a number literal, or an error
    leaf. A primary is the highest-precedence form.

17. Fold multiplication and division onto an accumulator, left-associatively, by
    parsing the next primary and recursing.

18. Parse a multiplicative expression: a primary followed by any number of times
    or divide operations.

19. Fold addition and subtraction onto an accumulator, left-associatively, by
    parsing the next multiplicative expression and recursing.

20. Parse an additive expression: a multiplicative expression followed by any
    number of plus or minus operations. Multiply and divide bind tighter than
    plus and minus.

21. Evaluate an arithmetic AST to a number, recursing on the tree and dispatching
    each binary node on its operator.

22. End to end: tokenize the source, parse an additive expression from the start,
    and evaluate the resulting AST. This proves precedence parsing: two plus
    three times four is fourteen, not twenty.
